Here is the straightforward way to see it by rewriting each radicand as a perfect power.

a)  \sqrt[4]{81\,x^{12}}

  81 x^{12}=(3^4)\,(x^3)^4, 
  so 
  \sqrt[4]{81\,x^{12}}
  =\sqrt[4]{(3\,x^3)^4}
  =|3\,x^3|
  =3\,|x|^3.

  (If one assumes x≥0, this simply becomes 3x^3.)

b)  \sqrt[6]{64\,y^{18}}

  64 y^{18}=(2^6)\,(y^3)^6,
  so
  \sqrt[6]{64\,y^{18}}
  =\sqrt[6]{(2\,y^3)^6}
  =|2\,y^3|
  =2\,|y|^3.

  (If y≥0, this is just 2y^3.)

To simplify \(49^{\tfrac{3}{2}}\), rewrite the exponent as a root and a power:

\[
49^{\tfrac{3}{2}}
= \bigl(49^{\tfrac12}\bigr)^{3}
= (\sqrt{49})^{3}
= 7^{3}
= 343.
\]

Using the law of exponents \(\frac{a^m}{a^n}=a^{m-n}\), we get

\[
\frac{w^{3/4}}{w^{7/4}}
= w^{\tfrac{3}{4}-\tfrac{7}{4}}
= w^{-1}
= \frac1w,
\]

valid for \(w\neq0\).
